<h2>Spa Etiquette in Mallorca</h2>

<p>If you''re visiting a Mallorcan spa for the first time, understanding local etiquette will help you feel comfortable and get the most from your experience.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Arrival time:</strong> Arrive 15–20 minutes before your appointment to complete any intake forms, change into your robe and slippers, and begin to relax. Late arrivals may result in shortened treatment times.</li>
  <li><strong>What to wear:</strong> Most spas provide robes and slippers. In thermal circuit areas, swimwear is typically required (unlike some German or Scandinavian spas where nudity is the norm). Bring a swimsuit, or check with the spa if they sell disposable options.</li>
  <li><strong>Silence and phones:</strong> Spa areas are quiet zones. Mobile phones should be silenced and ideally left in your locker. Photography is generally prohibited in treatment and relaxation areas.</li>
  <li><strong>Tipping:</strong> Tipping is not obligatory in Spanish spas, but is appreciated for excellent service. A tip of €5–€10 per treatment, or 10% of the treatment cost, is generous.</li>
  <li><strong>Communication with your therapist:</strong> Do not hesitate to speak up about pressure preferences, temperature comfort, or any discomfort during a treatment. Professional therapists welcome feedback and will adjust their technique accordingly.</li>
  <li><strong>Hydration:</strong> Drink plenty of water before and after spa treatments, especially after thermal circuits, saunas, and body wraps. Most spas provide complimentary water, herbal teas, and fruit-infused water in their relaxation areas.</li>
  <li><strong>Cancellation policies:</strong> Most spas require 24–48 hours'' notice for cancellations. Late cancellations or no-shows typically incur a charge of 50–100% of the treatment cost.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Do I need to be a hotel guest to use the spas in Calvia?</h3>
<p>No, most spas in Calvia welcome non-hotel guests for both individual treatments and day spa packages. However, availability for external guests may be limited during peak season (June–September), and some ultra-luxury hotel spas (such as the St. Regis Mardavall) may restrict access to hotel guests only for certain facilities. It is always advisable to call ahead and book in advance, especially during the summer months. Standalone wellness centres like Pure Relax, Aqua Spa, and Harmony Spa are open to all visitors without any hotel stay requirement.</p>

<h3>What is the best time of year to visit a spa in Calvia?</h3>
<p>Autumn (September through November) is widely considered the best season for spa visits in Calvia. The summer crowds have departed, prices for treatments and packages are often reduced, the weather remains pleasantly warm, and the sea is still warm enough for outdoor thalassotherapy. Spring (March through May) is also excellent, with mild temperatures and easy availability. Summer is the busiest period, requiring advance booking, while winter offers a cosy, intimate spa experience and the best prices of the year.</p>

<h3>Is thalassotherapy different from a regular spa treatment?</h3>
<p>Yes, thalassotherapy is a specific discipline that uses heated seawater, marine algae, sea mud, and other ocean-derived products for therapeutic purposes. Unlike regular hydrotherapy, which uses treated freshwater, genuine thalassotherapy requires real seawater that retains its natural mineral content. The Elba Sunset Thalasso Spa in Palmanova is one of the few facilities in the Balearic Islands that meets the strict criteria for authentic thalassotherapy. Regular spa treatments may use freshwater in pools and jacuzzis, while thalassotherapy centres pump and heat actual Mediterranean seawater. For a comprehensive overview, visit our <a href="/blog/thalassotherapy-mallorca">guide to thalassotherapy in Mallorca</a>.</p>

<h3>Are spa treatments safe during pregnancy?</h3>
<p>Some spa treatments can be enjoyed during pregnancy, but many come with restrictions. Most spas in Calvia offer prenatal massage by specially trained therapists, using gentle techniques and positioning that is safe and comfortable for pregnant women. However, saunas, steam rooms, hot tubs, and very hot water immersion are generally not recommended during pregnancy due to the risk of overheating. Similarly, certain essential oils used in aromatherapy are contraindicated during pregnancy. Always inform the spa that you are pregnant when booking, and consult your midwife or obstetrician before any spa treatments. The spa will then tailor the experience to ensure your safety and comfort.</p>

<h3>How much should I budget for a spa day in Calvia?</h3>
<p>A spa day in Calvia can range from approximately €80 for a basic treatment at a mid-range spa to over €400 for a premium full-day package at a luxury hotel spa. A reasonable mid-range budget would be €120–€180 per person for a half-day experience including thermal circuit access and one treatment. If you''re on a tighter budget, standalone spas like Pure Relax and Aqua Spa offer individual treatments from €65, and morning or weekday specials can provide further savings. For the ultimate luxury experience, budget €250–€400 per person at the St. Regis Mardavall or Castillo Son Vida.</p>

<h3>Can I get spa treatments for chronic pain or medical conditions?</h3>
<p>Many spa treatments in Calvia can complement medical treatment for chronic pain, arthritis, fibromyalgia, and other conditions. Hydrotherapy and thalassotherapy, in particular, have evidence supporting their use for musculoskeletal conditions. However, spa treatments should be seen as complementary to, not a replacement for, medical care. Always consult your doctor before beginning any spa-based treatment programme for a medical condition, inform your therapist about your condition and any medications, and start with gentler treatments to assess your body''s response before progressing to more intensive options.</p>

<h3>Are there any spas in Calvia with facilities for children?</h3>
<p>Most spa areas in Calvia are adults-only environments (typically 16+ or 18+), as the quiet, relaxation-focused atmosphere is not compatible with young children. However, several hotels that house spas — including the Meliá South Beach and Elba Sunset — have separate family pool areas and kids'' clubs, allowing parents to alternate spa time with family time. Some spas offer specific teen treatments (such as facials for young skin) for guests aged 14–17 with parental consent. If you are travelling with children and want to enjoy a spa experience, consider booking a babysitter through your hotel or choosing a spa that is part of a family-friendly resort.</p>

<h3>What should I do if I have skin allergies or sensitivities?</h3>
<p>If you have known allergies or sensitivities, always inform the spa at the time of booking and again when you arrive. Reputable spas in Calvia will conduct a skin patch test before applying new products and can substitute products in their treatments to avoid your specific allergens. Many spas carry hypoallergenic and fragrance-free product lines for sensitive clients. If you have severe allergies (particularly to nuts, as some massage oils contain nut-derived ingredients), make this absolutely clear before any treatment begins. The spa should be able to provide a full list of ingredients in any products they plan to use.</p>

